data.title: Digital Paintings of (mostly) Waterfalls
data.description:
Final waterfall count: 87 +/- 1. "Mostly" achieved.

I have been a fan of digital art for over 20 years now, collecting digital paintings of landscapes, characters, and vehicles in the science fiction, medieval fantasy, cyberpunk, steampunk, and dieselpunk genres. For some bizarre reason I still haven't figured out, my favorite subject is waterfalls. Waterfalls in forests, under castles, breaking through ruins, and cascading in derelict spacecraft. 

I thought I'd share some of my collection of waterfalls. Some of these have appeared on Imgur before, I'm sure, but I only obtained one of these here. I'll let you guess which one. I tried to include the name of the painting and the artist with each image, for proper credit. Most of the images are wallpaper sized for various desktops, but this isn't specifically a "wallpaper dump." Any information on #34, #51, #52, #53, or #62 would be appreciated. All four of these came from some collection of wallpapers I got at least got six years ago.

There is, unsurprisingly, a good subreddit for this called "Imaginary Waterfalls": https://old.reddit.com/r/ImaginaryWaterfalls/ (Reddit's "new" design sucks).

Honorable Mentions: These are artists' pages I found while looking for the artists' pages that appear in this dump. They have some beautiful work, but nothing of theirs appears here.
https://www.deviantart.com/atomhawk

https://www.artstation.com/bazyzzy (Check out his "Waterfall" painting)

I may do another one of these, but it would have a different theme: abstract...shapes...and shit.

data.title: Field Trip to Iguazu Falls, Argentina side

images.description: I just wanted to share with you guys my experience on a trip to Argentina a few years back for field trip week. I did y'all a favor and removed the audio from the videos so you don't have to hear my annoying "oh my GOD" commentary.

First on the agenda is a train ride to Devil's Throat. The Devil's Throat canyon is 80–90 m (260–300 ft) wide and 70–80 m (230–260 ft) deep and we will be walking to it, using walkways over the water.
